            <h2>How Our Seeds Were Planted</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.2em; color: #666; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
                Born from the understanding that traditional top-down approaches fail to create lasting change, 
                A Curious Tractor emerged as a different way of working‚Äîone that puts communities in the driver's seat.
            </p>
        </div>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr)); gap: 40px; align-items: start;">
            <div>
                <h3 style="color: var(--act-empathy); margin-bottom: 20px;">üå∞ The First Seed</h3>
                <p>In 2019, while working with First Nations communities on storytelling projects, we kept hearing the same challenge: 
                <em>"We have the solutions, but we need tools that we own and control."</em></p>
                <p>Traditional social impact work was extractive‚Äîtaking stories, data, and knowledge without giving communities real agency. 
                That's when we asked: What if we designed every tool for obsolescence? What if success meant communities no longer needed us?</p>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h3 style="color: var(--act-seedling); margin-bottom: 20px;">üöú Learning from the Land</h3>
                <p>The tractor metaphor emerged from conversations with Traditional Owners about regenerative agriculture. 
                A tractor's power take-off (PTO) transfers energy from the engine to external tools‚Äîplows, harvesters, pumps. 
                The tractor doesn't do the farming; it empowers other tools to do their work.</p>
                <p>That's exactly what community-led change needs: infrastructure that transfers capacity without imposing control.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h3 style="color: var(--act-sunrise); margin-bottom: 20px;"><span style="color: var(--act-seedling);">‚óÜ</span> Growing from Small Seeds</h3>
                <p>We started small‚Äîa community garden, storytelling workshops, a repair cafe. Each project taught us more about deep listening, 
                community ownership, and the intersection of traditional knowledge with modern tools.</p>
                <p>Today, ACT operates four flagship platforms demonstrating regenerative innovation at scale, 
                all owned and governed by the communities they serve. We've learned that the best solutions grow slowly, with deep roots.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 50px; padding: 40px; background: var(--act-cream); border-radius: 16px;">
            <p style="font-size: 1.2em; color: var(--act-soil); font-style: italic; margin: 0;">
                "We named ourselves A Curious Tractor because curiosity drives innovation, and like a tractor in the field, 
